**Wash and dry all produce.** Bring water to a boil in a #small pot{}. Halve 
@zucchini{1} lengthwise, then slice into thin half-moons. Trim, then thinly slice 
@button mushrooms{4%ounce}. Finely chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}. Halve, peel, and 
mince @shallot{1}. Set aside @flour{2%tbsp} for sauce, then place the rest in a 
#shallow dish{}.

Once water is boiling, add @basmati rice{1%pack} to #pot{}. Cover, reduce to a 
simmer, and cook until tender, ~{20%minutes}. Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} 
in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add zucchini and cook, tossing, until nicely 
browned, ~{10%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove pan from heat.

With your hand on one @chicken breasts{12%ounce}, cut ¾ of the way through center, 
parallel to #cutting board{}, stopping before you slice through. Open it up, cover 
with #plastic wrap{}, and pound with a heavy pan or #mallet{} until ½ inch thick. 
Repeat with remaining chicken breast. Season both with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then 
toss in remaining flour in shallow dish to coat, shaking off excess.

Heat a drizzle of oil in another large pan over medium-high heat. Add chicken and 
cook until browned and no longer pink in center, ~{3%minutes} per side. Remove 
from pan and set aside to rest. Meanwhile, cook rice in #microwave{} according to 
package instructions.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in pan used to cook chicken over medium-high heat. Add 
mushrooms and cook, tossing, until tender, ~{5%minutes}. Add shallot and 
@butter{1%tbsp} and cook, tossing, until butter melts, ~{2%minutes}. Add reserved 
flour and stir for ~{1%minute}. Whisk in @chicken stock concentrate{1} and water 
and let sauce thicken, ~{2%minutes} more.

Reduce heat under pan to low. Stir in @sour cream{2%tablespoon} and half the parsley. 
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. If zucchini has cooled, quickly reheat in pan. 
Divide rice, zucchini, and chicken between plates. Drizzle sauce over everything, 
garnish with remaining parsley, and serve.

> Scallopini get their name from the Italian word for "scallops," or a thinly sliced 
> piece of meat. This dish transforms chicken breasts into slim and slender cutlets 
> just the way they do at many a trattoria. The scallopini are dusted in flour to 
> give them a crispy brown coating and smothered in a creamy mushroom sauce that 
> truly tastes like amore at first bite.